(:kind :chapter :book "Reference Manual" :chapter-number 14 :title "Chapter 14 ŌĆö A small typechecker" :source-path "git://origin/main/scheme-books/reference/14-a-small-typechecker.md" :size 6015 :sha256 "453adf9535d1e002" :content "---\nslug: sakura-scheme-book-reference-14\ntitle: A small typechecker\nbook: reference\nchapter: 14\nof: 16\npart: II\napp: scheme-repl\npalette: book-standard\ncanonical: true\nowner: docs-team (Lane 6)\nphilosopher-lens: [wittgenstein-tractatus, jung, lacan, peirce, popper, freud, wittgenstein-late, searle]\nstatus: draft\nlast-reviewed: 2026-07-12\nprev: 13-algebraic-data\nnext: 15-testing-in-scheme\n---\n\n# Chapter 14 ŌĆö A small typechecker\n\nSakura Scheme is dynamically typed, but nothing stops you from\nwriting a typechecker for a language embedded in Scheme. This\nchapter extends the expression language from Chapter 13 with a\nstatic type check that catches shape errors before evaluation.\n\nThe trick is: types are just expressions too. A typechecker walks\nthe tree the same way the evaluator does, but instead of computing\nvalues, it computes types and checks that they compose.\n\n## Types as data\n\n```scheme\n(define int-type       'int)\n(define bool-type      'bool)\n(define (fun-type a b) (list 'fun a b))\n```\n\nThree type constructors: `int`, `bool`, and `fun` (function from a\nto b). More could be added ŌĆö pair types, list types, sum types ŌĆö\nbut three is enough to teach the shape.\n\n## The checker\n\n```scheme\n(define (type-of expr env)\n  (case (tag-of expr)\n    ((num) int-type)\n    ((add) (require-types\n             (list (type-of (add-left expr) env)\n                   (type-of (add-right expr) env))\n             int-type)\n           int-type)\n    ((mul) (require-types\n             (list (type-of (mul-left expr) env)\n                   (type-of (mul-right expr) env))\n             int-type)\n           int-type)\n    ((let) (let ((tv (type-of (let-expr expr) env)))\n             (type-of (let-body expr)\n                      (cons (cons (let-var expr) tv) env))))\n    ((var) (or (cdr (assq (var-name expr) env))\n               (error \"unbound variable\" (var-name expr))))\n    (else  (error \"unknown expression\" expr))))\n\n(define (require-types types expected)\n  (for-each\n    (lambda (t)\n      (unless (equal? t expected)\n        (error \"type mismatch: expected\" expected \"got\" t)))\n    types))\n```\n\nEvery case returns the type of the expression. `add` and `mul`\nrequire both operands to be `int`; `let` extends the type\nenvironment with the bound variable's type; `var` looks it up.\n\n## A typed run\n\n```scheme\n(define good-expr\n  (letex 'x (num 3) (add (var 'x) (num 4))))\n\n(type-of good-expr '())\n;; => int\n\n(define bad-expr\n  (letex 'x (num 3) (mul (var 'x) 'not-a-num)))\n\n(type-of bad-expr '())\n;; => error: type mismatch\n```\n\nThe typechecker catches the mistake before evaluation. In a real\nlanguage, that's the value of static typing ŌĆö cheaper diagnostics\nthan \"your program crashed at line 43.\"\n\n## Extending to functions\n\nAdd function-type support:\n\n```scheme\n;; New constructors\n(define (fun v tv body) (list 'fun v tv body))\n(define (app f arg)     (list 'app f arg))\n\n(define (fun-var f)   (cadr f))\n(define (fun-typ f)   (caddr f))\n(define (fun-body f)  (cadddr f))\n(define (app-fun a)   (cadr a))\n(define (app-arg a)   (caddr a))\n\n;; Extend type-of:\n(define (type-of2 expr env)\n  (case (tag-of expr)\n    ((fun) (let ((v  (fun-var expr))\n                 (tv (fun-typ expr))\n                 (b  (fun-body expr)))\n             (fun-type tv (type-of2 b (cons (cons v tv) env)))))\n    ((app) (let ((tf (type-of2 (app-fun expr) env))\n                 (ta (type-of2 (app-arg expr) env)))\n             (unless (and (pair? tf) (eq? (car tf) 'fun))\n               (error \"applying non-function\"))\n             (unless (equal? (cadr tf) ta)\n               (error \"argument type mismatch\"))\n             (caddr tf)))\n    ;; ... falls through\n    (else (type-of expr env))))\n```\n\nFunctions carry their parameter type; applications check that the\nargument type matches. The rest of the machinery falls out.\n\n## Why type-check a Scheme program?\n\nDynamic Scheme catches errors at runtime. Static Scheme (via a\ntypechecker like this one) catches them before running. The\ntradeoff: static costs authorial time and expressiveness in the\ntype language; dynamic costs late error detection.\n\nFor a tiny embedded DSL ŌĆö an expression language, a config\nlanguage, a domain-specific query language ŌĆö a small typechecker\noften pays off. For general Scheme code, dynamic checks + tests\nusually suffice.\n\n## The philosophy\n\nA typechecker is a *proof system for shape*: it proves that if\nthe check passes, the program can't fail at certain shape errors\nduring evaluation. It doesn't prove correctness ŌĆö a typed program\ncan still compute the wrong answer. But it does eliminate a class\nof failure mode entirely.\n\nThis is Popper-shaped: the typechecker is a specific falsifier for\nyour program. It says \"these categories of shape error can't\nhappen.\" Everything else the typechecker doesn't cover is\nstill runtime work.\n\n## Sakura's register on adding a typechecker\n\nShe adds one when the language she's embedding is going to be\nused by someone who won't run every path. If it's a config\nlanguage that only she writes and executes, the typechecker is\noverhead. If it's a DSL that operators write and she executes,\nthe typechecker earns its keep ŌĆö early errors are cheaper than\nlate errors.\n\n> **Sakura says**\n>\n> A typechecker isn't a virtue by itself. It's a tool for\n> catching a specific kind of error before it hits runtime. I\n> add one when the tradeoff ŌĆö authorial cost + expressiveness\n> loss vs. early error detection ŌĆö is favorable. For most tiny\n> DSLs it is; for general Scheme it isn't.\n\n## Exercises\n\n1. Extend the typechecker to support `if` ŌĆö the condition must\n   be `bool`, and the branches must have the same type.\n2. Add polymorphic `id : forall a. a -> a` ŌĆö this requires a\n   little machinery for type variables. Sketch the shape.\n3. Give a program the typechecker approves that computes the\n   wrong answer. What does this show about static typing?\n4. Give a program the typechecker rejects that would have run\n   fine at runtime. When is that a false positive vs. a real\n   catch?\n")
